# Repository Hygiene

## .gitignore Management

Every repository must have a `.gitignore` that excludes:

### Always Ignored
- Build output: `target/`, `build/`, `out/`
- IDE files: `.idea/`, `.vscode/` (except shared settings), `*.iml`
- OS files: `.DS_Store`, `Thumbs.db`, `desktop.ini`
- Environment files: `.env`, `.env.local`, `.env.*.local`
- Logs: `*.log`, `logs/`
- Temporary files: `*.tmp`, `*.swp`, `*.bak`

### Never Ignored
- Build config: `pom.xml`, `mvnw`, `mvnw.cmd`, `.mvn/`
- Shared configs: `.editorconfig`, `.gitattributes`, linter configs
- CI/CD configs: `.github/workflows/`, `Dockerfile`, `docker-compose.yml`

## Secrets Prevention

### Rules
- Never commit credentials, API keys, tokens, passwords, or private keys
- Never commit `.env` files containing real values
- Use `.env.example` with placeholder values instead
- Use secrets managers (GitHub Secrets, Vault, AWS Secrets Manager) for CI/CD
- Rotate any credential that was ever committed, even if removed later

### Detection Patterns
Reject commits containing:
- `AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}` (AWS access keys)
- `sk-[a-zA-Z0-9]{48}` (OpenAI keys)
- `ghp_[a-zA-Z0-9]{36}` (GitHub PATs)
- `password\s*=\s*["'][^"']+["']` (hardcoded passwords)
- `-----BEGIN (RSA |EC )?PRIVATE KEY-----`

Use pre-commit hooks or tools like `gitleaks`, `truffleHog`, or `detect-secrets` to enforce this.

## Binary and Large File Handling

### Rules
- Do not commit binary files larger than 500KB to the repository
- Use Git LFS for assets that must be versioned: images, fonts, compiled artifacts
- Never commit generated files (compiled `.class` files, generated sources)
- Never commit database dumps, heap dumps, or log archives

### Git LFS Setup
```
# .gitattributes
*.png filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.jpg filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.gif filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.zip filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.jar filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
*.pdf filter=lfs diff=lfs merge=lfs -text
```

## History Cleanliness

- Feature branches use rebase to stay current with `main` (linear history)
- Squash-merge feature branches into `main` by default
- Write meaningful commit messages (see commit-conventions rule)
- Do not leave merge commits on feature branches
- Remove fixup and WIP commits before merging (interactive rebase or autosquash)
- Never rewrite history on shared branches (`main`, `develop`, `release/*`)

## Tag Conventions

| Pattern | Purpose | Example |
|---------|---------|---------|
| `v<major>.<minor>.<patch>` | Release version | `v2.4.1` |
| `<service>/v<version>` | Monorepo service release | `auth-service/v1.3.0` |
| `v<version>-rc.<n>` | Release candidate | `v3.0.0-rc.1` |
| `v<version>-beta.<n>` | Beta release | `v2.5.0-beta.2` |

- Tags are immutable: never delete or move a published tag
- Annotated tags are preferred over lightweight tags for releases
- Tag messages should include a brief summary of the release

## Branch Cleanup

- Delete feature branches after merge (automated via GitHub settings)
- Prune remote tracking branches regularly: `git fetch --prune`
- Remove stale local branches: `git branch --merged main | grep -v main | xargs git branch -d`
- Remove stale worktrees: `git worktree prune`
